<subSubSection id="BEAAA2CF168667363B062BC3C0E003FD" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="59ABBF053A43F17AB68ADAAA8DE25134" pageNumber="244">
Etymology L 
<taxonomicName id="32D6C09E026480EB4C63B5BFEA9891AF" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34079" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole vafra Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vafra">vafra</taxonomicName>
, artful, craftful, allusion unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1FF49EC488DF34FF0107E4F1C6F285EE" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="91EE269C47F5128F0F52DA0267171028" pageNumber="244">
diagnosis A small, brown member of the 
<taxonomicName id="1266B2EF0923B2FE65624E3FC3B9389E" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142247" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Atta" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Atta diligens Smith" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="diligens">diligens</taxonomicName>
group, whose major has a faintly bicolorous head; smooth anterior third of the head dorsal surface; abundant medium-length pilosity; relatively short antennal scapes, which are curved near their base; and equilaterally triangular postpetiolar spine in side view.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A61C6034C12352085AC06523F3F44120" type="description">
<paragraph id="CD159E05A1E92B3678C3F4D909B2D8AE" pageNumber="244">
Close to 
<taxonomicName id="19853EF2EBA857F06E43359F098CC044" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33625" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole blumenauensis Kempf" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blumenauensis">blumenauensis</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="967D67BB45D89F3B87835919E73971C3" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181688" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole perryorum Wilson" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="perryorum">perryorum</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="775FFEEAA943E813436DCA78AF759A01" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181680" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole rochai Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rochai">rochai</taxonomicName>
, but major differing in its shorter scapes, eyes larger than in 
<taxonomicName id="C9127DDA24133F72DF021891487976FE" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:181680" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole rochai Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="rochai">rochai</taxonomicName>
(but not in 
<taxonomicName id="1E01441600E8A2F2F01FCAD571EE6B3F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33625" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole blumenauensis Kempf" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="blumenauensis">blumenauensis</taxonomicName>
) and other details of body form and sculpturing in both major and minor, as illustrated. See also less similar 
<taxonomicName id="6DD3CE2519EC01196876A229ED635742" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33818" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole laevifrons Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="laevifrons">laevifrons</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="A1F570B860F3204599D906A9F8528A27" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33827" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole lemur Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lemur">lemur</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="87DB7938E5975D4414BDA347809B5A6E" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33922" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole peregrina Wheeler" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peregrina">peregrina</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName id="220DD4BEE25B72807A0D7054BC8CB7E4" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33945" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole pubiventris Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pubiventris">pubiventris</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="90F49E6B99D7B8E39932ADEA0F6C47A9" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:33996" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole seeldrayersi Forel" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="seeldrayersi">seeldrayersi</taxonomicName>
. Measurements (mm) Lectotype major: HW 0.96, HL 1.04, SL 0.74, EL 0.20, PW 0.54. Paralectotype minor: HW 0.52, HL 0.64, SL 0.74, EL 0.14, PW 0.36.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C6F36240CE0934F73718F3F6387DB65" pageNumber="244">Color Major: gaster medium brown, rest of body light brown except for anterior one-fourth of head capsule, which is a slightly contrasting brownish yellow. Minor: concolorous medium brown.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="A728C0B5D2B9F5C2FD7C97D362BD549A" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="D4AD32559C43391DB853EB88369E451E" pageNumber="244">
Range This hitherto obscure species turns out to be one of the most widespread of all New World 
<taxonomicName id="EB53448D2B3BAC8C7A6112A1B8FEDDB3" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:24885" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole Westwood" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Pheidole</taxonomicName>
. Its records, most of which I have been able to verify, include Nicaragua, Venezuela, Trinidad, Tobago, French Guiana, Amazonian Brazil, Argentina, and Paraguay.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="1AD4F88BC672959501E6F29B3E13FBCC" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph id="90B786CC740A8FCA2999FCF7611B676D" pageNumber="244">
Biology The very wide distribution of the species suggests that 
<taxonomicName id="C37DDD3682BE7D22D899D4D97C7D9235" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:34079" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.completionEvidence="missing, matching species" genus.innerRound="1" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole vafra Santschi" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="vafra">vafra</taxonomicName>
may be carried by human commerce. In any case, it inhabits marginal habitats. I found nests common in sandy soil at two localities along the southern coast of Tobago, where it coexists with the very widespread marginal-habitat specialist 
<taxonomicName id="1D8C0C8E2B2877EC069DEC9CB674688B" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:142274" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Pheidole" genus.outerRound="1" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Pheidole jelskii Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="244" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="jelskii">P. jelskii</taxonomicName>
. Near the Nariva Swamp of Trinidad, Stefan Cover found a colony at the border between a coconut grove and mangrove swamp, nesting under a fallen coconut leaf in sand; and a second colony at 550 m in Trinidad's Arima Valley, nesting in the hard-packed clay of a road running through a small coffee plantation.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="80E34659520C77746D66DC39CB3C05EB" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="5C914C17B4A89841C07C719FFDC55D5F" pageNumber="244">Figure Upper: lectotype, major. BRAZIL: Blumenau, Santa Catarina. (Outer antennal scape is from near Nariva Swamp, Trinidad.) Lower: minor. TRINIDAD: near Nariva Swamp (compared with paralectotype minor). Scale bars = 1 mm.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
